me as F.B. Pinkerton. In the third and subsequent versions, the libretto reverts to \'Benjamin Franklin Pinkerton\', the name used in the source short story. Mark D Lew, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://home.earthlink.net/~markdlew/lib/butterfly/mbutfn.htm#fn1">Footnote to the opera\'s libretti</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The creator of the role, <a href="/wiki/Emilio_Venturini" title="Emilio Venturini">Emilio Venturini</a>, was a <a href="/wiki/Tenor" title="Tenor">tenor</a>. The American Ricordi 2-act score from 1905, accessible below from <a href="/wiki/Indiana_University" title="Indiana University">Indiana University</a>, lists the role as <a href="/wiki/Baritone" title="Baritone">baritone</a> but the music is notated in the G-<a href="/wiki/Clef" title="Clef">clef</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Tessitura" title="Tessitura">tessitura</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vocal_range" title="Vocal range">range</a> of the role of Prince Yamadori is such that a number of baritones have also performed the role.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-autogenerated1-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-autogenerated1_21-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-autogenerated1_21-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://opera.stanford.edu/Puccini/creators.html">Creators of the operas of Giacomo Puccini \xe2\x80\x93 Role creators</a>, <a href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford University">Stanford University</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The "standard" version refers to Puccini\'s final set of revisions, published by Ricordi in 1907.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></spa